  "stage": {
    "id": "course_transformer_core",
    "stageNumber": 2,
    "title": "The Transformer Core",
    "roomWidth": 20,
    "roomHeight": 15,
    "concepts": [
      {
        "id": "scaled_dot_product_attention",
        "title": "Scaled Dot-Product Attention",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- queries, keys, values abstraction\n- √d_k scaling factor\n\nVaswani et al. (2017) compute attention as softmax(QKᵀ/√d_k)V; the √d_k divisor prevents large dot products from pushing softmax into saturation where gradients vanish. Queries, keys, and values are learned projections of the input.",
        "position": {
          "x": 5,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "multi_head_attention",
        "title": "Multi-Head Attention",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- 8 parallel heads in base model\n- concatenate and project outputs\n\nThe Transformer (Vaswani et al., 2017) runs h=8 attention heads in parallel, each learning different relational patterns, then concatenates and projects the results. Think of 8 experts each highlighting different word relationships.",
        "position": {
          "x": 9,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "positional_encoding",
        "title": "Positional Encoding",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- sine/cosine at varying frequencies\n- added to input embeddings\n\nBecause self-attention treats input as a set (not a sequence), Vaswani et al. add sinusoidal positional encodings to token embeddings so the model can distinguish position 1 from position 100. The sin/cos pattern lets it generalize to unseen sequence lengths.",
        "position": {
          "x": 13,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "transformer_architecture",
        "title": "The Transformer Architecture",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- 6 encoder + 6 decoder layers\n- residual connections + layer norm\n\nVaswani et al. (2017) stack 6 identical encoder and 6 decoder layers, each using only attention and feed-forward sublayers with residual connections — zero recurrence or convolution. This makes it highly parallelizable on GPUs.",
        "position": {
          "x": 5,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "feed_forward_sublayer",
        "title": "Position-wise Feed-Forward Network",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- inner dimension 2048\n- applied position-by-position\n\nEach Transformer layer includes FFN(x)=max(0,xW₁+b₁)W₂+b₂ applied identically and independently to every position (d_model=512, inner dim=2048). The same weights are reused across positions but learned separately from the attention sublayer.",
        "position": {
          "x": 9,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "encoder_decoder_stacks",
        "title": "Encoder-Decoder Stacks & Residual Connections",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- LayerNorm(x + Sublayer(x))\n- cross-attention in decoder\n\nVaswani et al. wrap every sublayer as LayerNorm(x + Sublayer(x)), combining residual connections with layer normalization for training stability. The decoder adds a third cross-attention sublayer that attends to the encoder output.",
        "position": {
          "x": 13,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      }
    ],
    "quiz": {
      "id": "quiz-stage-2",
      "question": "What is the formula for each sublayer's output in the Transformer? Answer with a number.",
      "type": "multiple-choice",
      "options": [
        "Sublayer(x) + x",
        "LayerNorm(x + Sublayer(x))",
        "LayerNorm(Sublayer(x))"
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "LayerNorm(x + Sublayer(x))",
      "position": {
        "x": 18,
        "y": 7
      }
